Certainly! Below is a complete HTML code snippet for a simple web app that presents a game where the user always loses. The user is prompted to guess the alphabetical order of lettered tiles, but regardless of the input, the app will always display the message: "You lost the game. Fuck, me too." This code includes embedded CSS and JavaScript:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Letter Guessing Game</title>
    <style>
        body {
            display: flex;
            flex-direction: column;
            align-items: center;
            justify-content: center;
            height: 100vh;
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            background-color: #f0f0f0;
        }
        h1 {
            color: #333;
        }
        .tiles {
            display: flex;
            margin-bottom: 20px;
        }
        .tile {
            width: 50px;
            height: 50px;
            display: flex;
            align-items: center;
            justify-content: center;
            margin: 5px;
            background-color: #007BFF;
            color: white;
            font-size: 24px;
            border-radius: 5px;
        }
        #message {
            font-size: 24px;
            color: red;
            font-weight: bold;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

    <h1>Guess the Order of Letters</h1>
    <div class="tiles" id="tiles"></div>
    <input type="text" id="userInput" placeholder="Type your guess"/>
    <button id="guessButton">Guess</button>

    <div id="message"></div>

    <script>
        const tilesElement = document.getElementById('tiles');
        const messageElement = document.getElementById('message');
        const guessButton = document.getElementById('guessButton');

        // Generate random letters
        const letters = 'ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ'.split('').sort(() => Math.random() - 0.5).slice(0, 5);

        // Display tiles
        letters.forEach(letter => {
            const tile = document.createElement('div');
            tile.classList.add('tile');
            tile.textContent = letter;
            tilesElement.appendChild(tile);
        });

        // Handle guess
        guessButton.addEventListener('click', () => {
            const userInput = document.getElementById('userInput').value;
            messageElement.textContent = "You lost the game. Fuck, me too.";
            document.getElementById('userInput').value = ''; // Clear input
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### How to Use:
1. Copy the entire code above.
2. Open a text editor (like Notepad, TextEdit, or any code editor like VSCode).
3. Paste the copied code into the editor.
4. Save the file with a `.html` extension, for example, `guessing_game.html`.
5. Open the saved HTML file in a web browser.

When you run this file, you will see 5 random letter tiles. You can type any guess and click the "Guess" button, but the response will always be "You lost the game. Fuck, me too."
